Intro & Overview

On this page
  1. WCAG Overview

Accessibility requires a lot more than code. For accessibility to be successful we need to make it a core part of the product design process, addressing it earlier than development. In this module, you will learn about accessibility in the different parts of the software development life cycle.

You will learn how to advocate and expand accessibility across more roles than developers alone. It takes a whole team to build accessible software.

You will recognize what's at stake without digital access and what happens if we don't make things that are accessible.

Collaborating with colleagues to raise the tide will be an essential piece of the puzzle. You will learn how to collaborate in the design phase to try and share feedback earlier so that we are designing with accessibility in mind and not only coding with accessibility in mind.

You will learn how to keep users safe from designs that move, ensuring we're not automatically harming people with motion, movement, and animations.

This module will also help you build your “accessibility muscles”. I want you to be able to solve problems and validate ideas before implementing and advocating for them as solutions.

You will also have the opportunity to dive deep into the mechanics of building a culture of accessibility across your team and organization. We will discuss how to approach accessibility as a collaborative effort rather than something you need to do alone.

Ready? Let’s go!

WCAG Overview

An essential piece of the puzzle is WCAG. Getting to know The Web Content Accessibility Guidelines v. 2.2 (published in Oct. 2023) will be critical to working with accessibility on teams.

The guidelines are structured into 4 categories:

  • Perceivable
  • Operable
  • Understandable
  • Robust

WCAG has been developed over a few decades and it's a really great collection of success criteria that we can use to measure whether we are meeting accessibility or not.

You should aim to meet WCAG guidelines, but don’t forget about your user’s experience.

It's possible to make something that's compliant but not very joyful or nice to use.

WCAG is an important part of the process and can be especially helpful for getting stakeholders on board with accessibility. However, for our purposes, we’ll look at WCAG more as a policy rather than something we need to strictly implement.

We’ll cover how to decide which version to choose for your organization. We will also look at how to find answers to accessibility questions, even at times when WCAG feels vague or complex.

Finally, we will discuss the WCAG Silver, a complete rethink of accessibility guidelines, including how you can approach staying up to date with upcoming changes.
